ey, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom","Brabourne, Kent, England":"Brabourne, Kent, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Calverley,","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Yorkshire and Lancashire): habitational name from Calverley in Yorkshire, named with Old English <i>calfra</i> (genitive plural of <i>calf</i> ‘calf’) + <i>lēah</i> ‘woodland clearing’. Alternatively, in some instances the name may be a variant of the habitational name <b>Calveley</b>, from a place so called in Cheshire (with the same meaning as above), or from Calverleigh in Devon, meaning ‘the clearing of the bare wood’ (Old English <i>calu</i> ‘bare, bald’ + <i>wudu</i> ‘wood’ + <i>lēah</i> ‘woodland clearing’)."],"variants":[{"name":"Calvery","meanings":["English: shortened form of   Calverley  .","Possibly an Americanized form of German <b>Kälberer</b>(see   Kalberer  )."]},{"name":"Caverly","meanings":["English (Middlesex): shortened form of   Calverley  ."]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["As a boy's name this represents a revival of Middle English <i>Jan</i>, a by‐form of   John  , or an adoption of the common European form with this spelling. As a girl's name it is a short form of names such as   Janet   and   Janice ."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Scott","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Although this was in use as a personal name both before and after the Norman Conquest, modern use in most cases almost certainly represents a transferred use of the surname. This originated as a byname for someone from Scotland or, within Scotland itself, for a member of the Gaelic-speaking people who originally came from Ireland. The given name is now often chosen by parents conscious of their Scottish ancestry and heritage, but it is also used more widely."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Lord John Scott de Calverley, I was born in 1075, in Edinburgh, Scotland, United Kingdom, his father, William Scott de Calverley, was 20 and his mother, Matilda de Kevelioc, was 17. He married Matilda, Queen of Scotland. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died on 24 May 1153, in England, United Kingdom, at the age of 78."},"et":{"1075–24 May 1153":"1075–24. mai 1153","1075–1153":"1075–1153","1072–1130":"1072–1130","1090–1138":"1090–1138","1055–1153":"1055–1153","1059–1130":"1059–1130","1090":"1090","1138":"1138","1059":"1059","23 April 1130":"23. aprill 1130","24 May 1153":"24. mai 1153","1055":"1055","1153":"1153","1075":"1075","1130":"1130","1072":"1072","Edinburgh, Lothian, Scotland":"Edinburgh, Šotimaa, United Kingdom","England":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Scone, Perthshire, Scotland":"Scone, Perthshire, Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Calverley, Yorkshire, England":"Calverley, Yorkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Brabourne, Kent, England":"Brabourne, Kent, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1075–24 May 1153":"1075–24. toukokuuta 1153","1075–1153":"1075–1153","1072–1130":"1072–1130","1090–1138":"1090–1138","1055–1153":"1055–1153","1059–1130":"1059–1130","1090":"1090","1138":"1138","1059":"1059","23 April 113